# Code Review: app.js — Error Handling, Input Validation & Security

Here's my review of the current `app.js` with concrete improvement suggestions. The file is small, but it has several security and robustness gaps typical of early-stage Express apps.

## Issues Found

### 1. No global error handler
Uncaught errors in handlers will expose stack traces and crash the process. Express needs an explicit error-handling middleware.

### 2. No request body / query validation
The routes are currently read-only, but as soon as you add `POST /users` or query params (e.g. `/users?id=...`), untrusted input will flow straight in. No validation library is wired up.

### 3. Missing security headers
No `helmet` middleware — responses lack `X-Content-Type-Options`, `Strict-Transport-Security`, `Content-Security-Policy`, etc.

### 4. No rate limiting
`/users` and `/health` are unthrottled — trivial to abuse for enumeration or DoS.

### 5. No CORS policy
`cors` is neither enabled nor explicitly restricted. Default browser behavior is safer, but once you add auth cookies or a frontend, you need an explicit allow-list.

### 6. `app.listen` has no error handling
`EADDRINUSE` or permission errors will throw unhandled.

### 7. No `process` hardening
No handlers for `uncaughtException` / `unhandledRejection`, no graceful shutdown on `SIGTERM`.

### 8. PII leak risk
`/users` returns emails with no authentication. Even mock data should be behind auth in a template, so the pattern isn't copy-pasted insecurely.

### 9. No body size limits
When you add `express.json()`, always pass a `limit` — default is 100kb, but it's worth being explicit to prevent memory-pressure DoS.

### 10. Logging of errors
`console.log` for the startup message is fine; production needs a structured logger (pino/winston) with request-scoped IDs.

