# Review of `app.js` — Error Handling, Input Validation & Security

The app is small, but there are several meaningful gaps for a production-ready service. Here's a prioritized list of improvements.

## 1. Missing global error handling

Currently, any thrown error crashes the process or leaks stack traces. Express needs an explicit error-handling middleware (four-arg signature) registered last.

```js
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err); // swap for a real logger (pino/winston) that redacts secrets
  if (res.headersSent) return next(err);
  res.status(err.status || 500).json({ error: 'Internal Server Error' });
});

// Also catch unhandled rejections/exceptions at the process level
process.on('unhandledRejection', (reason) => console.error('unhandledRejection', reason));
process.on('uncaughtException', (err) => { console.error('uncaughtException', err); process.exit(1); });
```

Also, `app.listen` has no error handler — add `.on('error', ...)` to fail fast on `EADDRINUSE`.

## 2. No input validation

The routes don't accept input *yet*, but the moment they do, you need validation. Standardize on a schema validator (Zod, Joi, or `express-validator`) rather than hand-rolled checks:

```js
